==Old English==
===Etymology===
(Closely related to [[leod|lēod]] and [[leode|lēode]]).  From Germanic ''*leudi-'', from Indo-European ''*leudh-'' ‘to grow, come up’.  Cognates include Old Saxon [[liodan]], Old High German [[liotan]], Gothic [[𐌻𐌹𐌿𐌳𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[ἐλεύθερος]] ‘free, freeman’, Latin [[liber]] ‘free’, Old Irish [[luss]] ‘plant’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'le:odan/

===Verb===
'''lēodan''' (class II strong)
# to [[grow]]
#:''Of ðam twige ludon reðe wæstme'': from that branch sprang dire fruits.  (Cædmon's ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

